<TITLE> Snap polls seekers care little for people: PM </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May 8 (bdnews24.com)Prime minister Sheikh Hasina took a dig at the opposition on Friday when she said those who demanded snap polls just to dislodge her four-month-old government did not care for the people. "Some are asking for mid-term elections, some are talking about toppling the government asking the government to resign," she told a delegation of Buddhists that went to see her at residence, Jamuna, on Bouddha Purnima on Saturday. The delegation led by Parbatya Bouddha Sangha president Pragananda Mahathero exchanged greetings with the prime minister on the occasion. "This government has been in office for only four months. We're facing a multitude of barriers in running the country. The road isn't easy for us. Some were always trying to push the country into turmoil to settle political scores, she said and asked the people to stay alert to the threat. BNP joint secretary-general Abdullah Al Noman had said last week that mid-term elections may be held on charges of failure of the government. Opposition leader Khaleda Zia on May 2 had asked the government of her bitter rival Hasina to step down if it failed to provide gas, power, running water and jobs, which were the prime minister's campaign pledge
